    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Slide Into Poverty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barbara Commins letter seconds Bob Herbert's concerns about indebtedness and invisibility of the poor in discussing status of working Americans (Sept 4 column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Working Harder, Longer,'' by Bob Herbert (column, Sept. 4):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Working Harder, Longer,'' by Bob Herbert (column, Sept. 4):</p>
        <p>I was glad to see Mr. Herbert raise the issues of indebtedness and the invisibility of the poor in discussing the status of working Americans.  What are working Americans using their credit cards for: food, junk or e-trades? How often do we see TV programs giving people tips on how to handle credit more carefully? Is there a connection between credit-card debt and the 19 percent of children who live below the poverty line?</p>
        <p>If America's booming economy depends on people's using consumer credit beyond their means, thus creating poverty, do we really have a healthy economy?</p>
        <p>Let's ask Al Gore and George W. Bush.</p>
        <p>BARBARA COMMINS  San Francisco, Sept. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
